FedEx reported disappointing results for the last quarter, the delivery giant reducing year-round profit estimates as a result of low demand for transportation services and increased costs for its land transport division.
The company also said it plans to hire around 55,000 seasonal workers for the holiday period.
In the same period last year, FedEx announced that it would hire 50,000 seasonal workers for the holiday period.
The company’s shares fell by about 2.5 percent in pre-market trading, 45 minutes before Wednesday’s opening bell ring.
FedEx Corp. said it expects to earn between $10.40 and $10.90 for the fiscal year ending in May next year, 20 cents less, according to a previous estimate.
Analysts estimated the figure at $10.84, according to a FactSet survey.
The falling estimate comes despite an increase in prices by 4.9% on average, with the entry into force on January 4 and higher surcharges for the ground transportation of large or heavy packages, which will apply from November.
The company said it still expects earnings to increase compared to the previous year as a result of lower costs, higher revenues and the development of online commerce.
President and CEO Fred Smith said: “The firm faces a considerably weaker economic situation than expected, especially in terms of global production and trade.
Employment plans for the holidays were announced a day after the UPS competitor said it plans to hire 90,000-95,000 additional workers, about the same number of jobs it made last year.
In the quarter that ended August 31, FedEx earned $692 million, up 6% from the previous year.
Earnings per share were $2.42, below the average estimate of $2.44 per share made by 12 analysts who responded to the Zacks Investment Research survey.
Profit increased by 5%, to $12.3 billion.
Six analysts who participated in the Zacks survey estimated $12.23 billion.
FedEx has been hit in recent years by a decline in international priority transport, which has led to a stagnation of revenues recorded by its Express unit.
But the explosion in online shopping has overshadowed the results of the FedEx Ground division.
In the last quarter, ground division revenues increased by 29%, but operating revenues stagnated practically due to higher costs for large packages and own insurance.
The express unit recorded an increase in revenue due to higher base tariffs, while the revenue recorded by the freight division decreased due to rising costs.
At pre-market trading, about an hour before the opening, FedEx shares fell by $3.85 or 2.5% to $150.15.
Tuesday closed down 11% year-on-year and 17% from the record high on June 11.
On the occasion of the most anticipated meeting in recent years, those responsible for policy-making within the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide if it’s time to raise a key rate of interest.
Above them, at the end of the central bank’s meeting room, a mural of the United States will be carved.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, the Fed’s president, and his colleagues must put the nation’s economic interests above all else.
The Central Bank has received a double task from Congress: to maximize the employment rate in the U.S. and maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, the Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a decision too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the U.S. economy is prepared to be discussed by the unprecedented stimulus offered by the near-zero-year 2008 interest rate in force.
Even if most of the data indicates a strong growing economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already cautious about adding volatility by increasing the reference rate to federal funds — even by a quarter of a percent.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and the main aspects they will pursue,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I believe that if they were to seek an excuse not to increase the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the world market is enough to give them arguments to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus as to the decision the Fed will make, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of Bloomberg’s recently questioned economists have anticipated an increase in the interest rate this week.
But financial markets are expected to delay the Fed, a key indicator showing that the likelihood of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a decline on the stock market if the Fed raises interest rates, except where policymakers would mitigate the blow by promising that it would pass a long time until the next growth.
On Tuesday, industrial average Dow Jones rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The storm was triggered by expectations that the Fed’s decision-makers will keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising that the Fed is raising interest rates at this point,” Lonski said.
If the Fed’s decision makers were to do so, “they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in the financial markets.”
Other experts said an increase in interest rates would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed to be on track to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step toward slow tightening monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that he expected an increase in interest rates this year despite high objections from liberals as if more economic progress were needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, job market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years, and close to the level the Fed sees as total employment.
Salary gains showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fail to meet the central bank’s annual target, the Fed’s decision-makers said a key reason was the temporary effect of falling oil prices.
The economy “may face higher rates and needs them, given the strain on the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to enter fibrillations at the end of this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 16% below its record high in May, as investors feared slowing China’s economy would pull down global growth.
The market has declined somewhat this month, the Dow index is now around 10% below the May maximum.
For the Fed’s decision-making factors, market turmoil adds to the complex calculation of the moment of interest rate growth.
“Without what has happened in the financial markets and news of the weakening of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would be firmer in the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at UCLA’s Ziman Center for Real Estate and former Fed official.
Now, he predicts that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There’s a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there’s almost no data to back up on what’s happening in China,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so it should practically not be taken into account in making decisions.
However, in reality, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been enormous.
President Ben S. Bernanke’s simple suggestion in 2013 that the Fed could “squeeze” its monetary expansion has triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, it is expected that Fed officials will not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the global economy.
His decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of the global strategy department at the wealth management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that "The Fed has a history of over-reaction to changes in the financial market that appear to have nothing to do with economic bases."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported the increase in interest rates, offered as an example the 1998-99 decisions.
A financial crisis that affected Asia prompted the Fed to reduce the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, “despite the limited identification implications for U.S. development,” Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed officials returned to those declines.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England interest rate commission.
The last period of agitation does not even rise far to that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to get into a situation where we fear an increase in interest rates because markets have been upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds a double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this regard, I do not think it should take premature action.
