Four people lost their lives after police fired rubber bullets at protesters in Nepal
Four people, including a 4-year-old boy, were killed in southern Nepal after police shot rubber bullets in the crowd demonstrating against the country's proposed new constitution, an official said on Wednesday.
The violence took place on Tuesday evening in the Rupandehi district, about 280 km west of the capital Kathmandu.
According to Bishnu Prasad Dhakal, the head of the district police, more than 1,000 protesters gathered in front of a police department, and some of them threw stones and molotov cocktails.
Mr. Dhakal said police forces used tear gas after which they fired shots into the air before resorting to the use of rubber bullets.
